Certainly! Below is a simple web app that displays a calendar highlighting all Wednesdays in the month. The entire HTML, CSS, and JavaScript code are embedded within a single HTML file.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Wednesday Calendar</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            display: flex;
            flex-direction: column;
            align-items: center;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 50px;
            background-color: #f7f7f7;
        }
        h1 {
            margin-bottom: 20px;
        }
        .calendar {
            display: grid;
            grid-template-columns: repeat(7, 1fr);
            gap: 5px;
            width: 100%;
            max-width: 600px;
        }
        .day {
            padding: 20px;
            text-align: center;
            border: 1px solid #ddd;
            background-color: #fff;
            border-radius: 4px;
        }
        .wednesday {
            background-color: #ADD8E6; /* Light blue for Wednesdays */
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Calendar with Wednesdays Highlighted</h1>
    <div class="calendar" id="calendar"></div>

    <script>
        function createCalendar(year, month) {
            const calendar = document.getElementById('calendar');
            calendar.innerHTML = '';

            // Get the first day of the month and number of days in the month
            const firstDay = new Date(year, month, 1);
            const numberOfDays = new Date(year, month + 1, 0).getDate();
            const dayOffset = firstDay.getDay();

            // Create empty slots for days before the first day
            for (let i = 0; i < dayOffset; i++) {
                const emptyDiv = document.createElement('div');
                calendar.appendChild(emptyDiv);
            }

            // Add day elements to the calendar
            for (let day = 1; day <= numberOfDays; day++) {
                const dayDiv = document.createElement('div');
                dayDiv.className = 'day';
                dayDiv.textContent = day;

                // Highlight Wednesdays
                const date = new Date(year, month, day);
                if (date.getDay() === 3) { // 3 corresponds to Wednesday
                    dayDiv.classList.add('wednesday');
                }

                calendar.appendChild(dayDiv);
            }
        }

        // Get the current month and year
        const today = new Date();
        createCalendar(today.getFullYear(), today.getMonth());
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### How It Works
1. **HTML Structure**: The body contains a title and a div where the calendar will be populated.
2. **CSS**: Styles are embedded to format the calendar, style the days, and highlight Wednesdays.
3. **JavaScript**: A function `createCalendar` generates the calendar for the current month, identifying Wednesdays based on the `getDay()` method, and adds the appropriate class to highlight them.

This code can be copied and saved into an HTML file, and it will create a functional calendar highlighting all Wednesdays for the current month when opened in a web browser.

